{A big chess event was organised in Dresden from 4 until 14 iv 1926. The
fiftieth anniversary of the local chess club was celebrated! Main contest was
a master tournament, called the Paul Schellenberg Memorial. It became a race
between the world championship's candidates Nimzowitsch and Alekhine. Aaron
triumphed. Some of his wins became classics. Rubinstein competed in the race
until he was beaten by the top two. The fifth prize was won by the problem
composer Von Holzhausen. We follow the games by Nimzowitsch and Alekhine.  } 1.
Nf3 c5 2. g3 Nc6 3. Bg2 e5 4. e4 Be7 $5 5. O-O d6 {
This pawn formation will be called the Dresden Variation.} 6. c3 Bg4 7. d3 Qd7
8. Re1 Nf6 9. Nbd2 Rd8 10. Qa4 O-O 11. Qc2 Qc7 12. Nc4 h6 13. Ne3 Bd7 14. Nh4
Rfe8 15. f4 Qb8 16. Nhf5 Bf8 17. Qf2 Bxf5 18. Nxf5 d5 19. Rf1 dxe4 20. dxe4 Qc8
21. Qf3 Qe6 22. fxe5 Nd7 23. Qg4 Ndxe5 24. Qe2 Qc4 25. Qxc4 Nxc4 {
Black has an advantage in development.} 26. b3 Nd6 27. Nxd6 Bxd6 28. Be3 b6 29.
Rad1 $2 (29. Rac1 $1 Be5 30. Rf2 Rd3 31. Bd2 Red8 32. Rc2 $1 {
restores the white position.}) 29... Be5 $1 30. Bd2 Rd3 $1 31. Rf3 Rd6 32. Kf1
Red8 {Black applies a nasty pin.} 33. Ke2 c4 34. bxc4 Na5 35. Rff1 Nxc4 {
Nimzowitsch plays a fine endgame.} 36. Bf4 $4 ({Correct is} 36. Bc1 $1 Bxc3 37.
Rxd6 Rxd6 38. Rd1 b5 39. Rxd6 Nxd6 40. Kd3 Be5 41. Bh3 {
White has lifted the pressure at the cost of a pawn.}) 36... Rxd1 37. Rxd1 Rxd1
38. Kxd1 Bxf4 {Black wins a piece due to a fork.} 0-1

